AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation (Unsupervised Learning)¶

Background: AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending paterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

K-Means Clustering¶

In [18]:
# Finding optimal number of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters = range(1,21)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_scaled)
    prediction = model.predict(df_scaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_scaled.shape[0])

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, marker = 'o')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method');

Insights: From the above elbow method it seems like k = 3 is the distinct elbow point therefore we'll try k=3.

Conclusion¶

Comparing the K-means clusters to the Hierarchical clusters, we se that they are practically identical. They are giving the exact same Silhouette score for one. Also, the groups are split identically with 50, 224, 386 counts in each group. The only real difference is the hierarchical groups are reverse order than the K-means clustering groups, meaning that h_Group 3 is equivalent to k_Group 0, h_Group 2 equivalent to k_Group 2, and h_Group 1 equivalent to k_Group 2.

Knowing that we derived to 3 segments of customers, and these segments mirrored each other as outlined above betweeen the two methods, we'll outline how these segments were formed using the k_Group segmentation only, since the same can be said for the equivalent h_Group segments.

Specifically, you can see that k_Group 0 had the highest Average number of Visits to the Bank compared to the other two segments while also having the lowest online visits. While k_Group 1 segmented the customers with highest total calls made and lowest total credit cards in this group. Finally, the k_Group 2 was segmented by highest Average Credit Limit, highest Total number of Credit Cards as well as the most average Total visits online.

Looking at the segmentation from this analysis, it's clear that customers that fall into the k_Group 2 tend to have hiher Credit Limits and larger number of credit cards, but interestingly enough they also tend to rely on online banking more than the other groups. Therefore, making sure to have this group marketed any potential website or app products that could help them streamline their banking process would likely be appreciated by this group. Meanwhile, k_Group 1 tends to make the most phone calls yet has the lowest number of credit cards, which could lead AllLife to possibly target this group via direct phone calls to push any new products or services they may wish to promote to this group. Finally, k_Group 0 are the customer segments that seem to prefer showing up to the bank in person and use the online services the least. This group might not be the best segment to target online, yet may be the type of individuals who respond well to physical mail offers possibly flag these customers to have the tellers mention any promotion next time they come into the bank.
